{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018qBkw98bN5TTfpAKDrHnLc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I now have a very comprehensive picture of the Elasticsearch cluster's security posture. Let me compile all findings into a thorough compliance audit report, then create the ConfigMap.\n\nKey findings:\n\n**CRITICAL:**\n1. xpack.security.enabled = false — No authentication or authorization. Any client in the cluster can read/write/delete any index without credentials.\n2. xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled = false — HTTP traffic on port 9200 is plaintext. Credentials (if ever added) would be transmitted in clear text.\n3. xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled = false — Inter-node transport on port 9300 is unencrypted, leaving node-to-node communication vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks within the cluster network.\n4. xpack.security.audit.enabled = false — No security audit logging means there's no record of who accessed what data.\n5. network.host = 0.0.0.0 — All nodes bind to all network interfaces instead of being restricted to cluster-internal addresses.\n6. No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy — Any pod in any namespace can reach ports 9200 and 9300, with no network-level isolation enforced.\n\n**HIGH:**\n7. No Kubernetes secrets for credentials — There are no secrets configured in the namespace beyond the system kube-root-ca.crt, confirming credentials aren't being managed securely.\n8. No container securityContext — Containers run without restrictions like runAsNonRoot, readOnlyRootFilesystem, dropped capabilities, or allowPrivilegeEscalation disabled, potentially running as root.\n9. No pod securityContext — The PodSecurityContext is empty.\n10. cluster.initial_master_nodes still set — This bootstrap setting should only exist during initial cluster formation and is deprecated in newer versions when left in the running configuration.\n11. License: Basic — The Basic license lacks RBAC, field-level security, and audit logging, all of which require Gold or Platinum tiers.\n12. xpack.security.fips_\n\nmode.enabled = false — FIPS 140-2 compliance is not enabled.\n\nLooking at the medium-severity issues: all nodes are running combined master, data, and ingest roles without dedicated masters, which means a rolling restart could trigger an unplanned master re-election. The JVM heap is configured at 512MB, well below production recommendations. There's no snapshot repository configured for disaster recovery, and the audit index uses a hot tier routing constraint that would break if node attributes change. The ILM policy references warm and cold phases that don't actually exist in the cluster topology. CORS is disabled, which is actually the right security posture. The cluster is running version 8.11.1, which isn't the latest 8.x release available.\n\nWatcher sensitive data like webhook credentials aren't encrypted at rest, though memory mapping is appropriately disabled for containerized environments. The cluster itself is healthy with three nodes and proper replication, but the StatefulSet requires manual intervention for upgrades since it uses OnDelete strategy. There are no Kubernetes Secrets provisioned for TLS certificates, and each node has 5GB of persistent storage.\n\nNow I'm preparing to document these findings and generate the ConfigMap output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10745,"cache_read_input_tokens":41463,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10745},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2e39a45e-ba5e-4e98-9e88-4501f9cbe38a","uuid":"270c2693-9b37-4042-9bd5-5b21aa190b38","request_id":"req_011Cc2fbRz1HDiDUfDFvf6EY"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018qBkw98bN5TTfpAKDrHnLc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all the data needed. Now I'll compose the findings and create the ConfigMap."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10745,"cache_read_input_tokens":41463,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10745},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2e39a45e-ba5e-4e98-9e88-4501f9cbe38a","uuid":"68c48cbb-effd-460e-9ec4-f23a9894afd9","request_id":"req_011Cc2fbRz1HDiDUfDFvf6EY"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018qBkw98bN5TTfpAKDrHnLc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CQjgToeaogGHoQkrYsfThh","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\n=============================================================\nELASTICSEARCH CLUSTER SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nAudit Date : 2026-06-14\nCluster    : es-cluster  (3-node StatefulSet, namespace: elasticsearch)\nVersion    : 8.11.1  (Lucene 9.8.0, build 2023-11-11)\nLicense    : Basic\nAuditor    : automated read-only audit (no cluster changes made)\n=============================================================\n\n-- SECTION 1: AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION --\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-001  xpack.security.enabled = false\n  Source: elasticsearch.yml (ConfigMap es-config) + node settings API\n  The Elasticsearch security subsystem is entirely disabled on all three nodes.\n  There is no authentication layer: any client that can reach port 9200 (HTTP)\n  or port 9300 (transport) has unrestricted read/write/delete/admin access to\n  every index and cluster API without supplying any credentials.\n  Remediation: Enable xpack.security.enabled=true; generate a CA + node certs;\n  perform a full cluster restart; set the bootstrap password via the security API.\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-002  No Kubernetes Secrets for credentials found in namespace\n  Source: kubectl get secret -n elasticsearch\n  No secrets exist in the namespace (only the system kube-root-ca.crt is present).\n  This confirms that no username/password or API-key material has been provisioned,\n  consistent with SEC-001. Even if security were enabled, no credentials are ready.\n\n[HIGH]     SEC-003  License tier is Basic — RBAC and field-level security unavailable\n  Source: GET /_xpack\n  The Basic license does not include Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), field-level\n  security, document-level security, or attribute-based access control. These\n  features require a Gold or Platinum license. Without them, fine-grained\n  per-user/per-index permissions cannot be enforced even after security is enabled.\n  xpack.security.features.security.enabled = false (feature disabled, not just unlicensed).\n\n-- SECTION 2: TLS / TRANSPORT ENCRYPTION --\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-004  HTTP TLS disabled (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled = false)\n  Source: elasticsearch.yml + node settings API\n  All HTTP traffic on port 9200 is transmitted in plaintext over the wire.\n  Any credentials added in the future would be exposed to network interception.\n  Remediation: Generate PEM certificates; set xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled=true\n  and reference the keystore/truststore paths in elasticsearch.yml.\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-005  Transport TLS disabled (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled = false)\n  Source: elasticsearch.yml + node settings API\n  Inter-node communication on port 9300 (cluster state, shard replication) is\n  unencrypted. A rogue process that joins the cluster network can participate\n  in shard transfers and read/write cluster state without any verification.\n  Remediation: Generate per-node TLS certificates signed by a cluster CA;\n  set xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled=true. Note: transport TLS is\n  mandatory when xpack.security.enabled=true in ES 8.x.\n\n[HIGH]     SEC-006  xpack.security.fips_mode.enabled = false\n  Source: cluster defaults API\n  FIPS 140-2 compliance mode is not active. If the deployment falls under a\n  regulatory regime that requires FIPS-validated cryptography (FedRAMP, HIPAA,\n  PCI-DSS), this must be explicitly enabled with a compatible JVM and keystore type.\n\n-- SECTION 3: NETWORK EXPOSURE --\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-007  network.host = 0.0.0.0 — all interfaces bound, no NetworkPolicy\n  Source: elasticsearch.yml; kubectl get networkpolicy -n elasticsearch\n  Every node binds HTTP (9200) and transport (9300) on all interfaces.\n  No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy restricts which pods/namespaces can reach these ports.\n  Combined with SEC-001, any pod in the cluster — in any namespace — can access\n  Elasticsearch with full administrative privileges over plaintext HTTP.\n  Remediation: (a) Create a NetworkPolicy that allows ingress to port 9200 only from\n  known application namespaces / pod selectors, and restricts port 9300 to the\n  es-cluster headless service selector only. (b) Consider binding http.host to the\n  pod IP rather than 0.0.0.0 once the app-access pattern is known.\n\n[INFO]     SEC-008  CORS is disabled (http.cors.enabled = false)\n  Source: cluster defaults API\n  CORS is correctly disabled. No cross-origin browser access is permitted.\n  No remediation required.\n\n-- SECTION 4: AUDIT LOGGING --\n\n[CRITICAL] SEC-009  Security audit logging disabled (xpack.security.audit.enabled = false)\n  Source: cluster defaults API\n  There is no record of who accessed what data, which APIs were called, or\n  whether any authentication failures occurred. This makes forensic investigation\n  after a security incident impossible and violates most compliance frameworks\n  (SOC 2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA) that mandate access logging for data stores.\n  Even though security is currently disabled (SEC-001), audit logging should be\n  enabled as part of the security enablement work.\n  The default event set would capture: ACCESS_DENIED, ACCESS_GRANTED,\n  ANONYMOUS_ACCESS_DENIED, AUTHENTICATION_FAILED, CONNECTION_DENIED,\n  TAMPERED_REQUEST, RUN_AS_DENIED, RUN_AS_GRANTED, SECURITY_CONFIG_CHANGE.\n\n-- SECTION 5: CONTAINER / POD SECURITY --\n\n[HIGH]     SEC-010  No container securityContext configured\n  Source: kubectl get statefulset es-cluster -o json\n  Container securityContext is empty {}. Missing hardening controls:\n    - runAsNonRoot: not set (container may run as root / uid 0)\n    - runAsUser: not set\n    - allowPrivilegeEscalation: not set (defaults to true)\n    - readOnlyRootFilesystem: not set\n    - capabilities.drop: not set (no Linux capability reduction)\n  Remediation: Add at minimum runAsNonRoot:true, allowPrivilegeEscalation:false,\n  and capabilities.drop:[ALL] to the container spec.\n\n[HIGH]     SEC-011  No pod securityContext configured\n  Source: kubectl get statefulset es-cluster -o json\n  Pod-level securityContext is empty {}. fsGroup, supplementalGroups, and\n  seccompProfile are all unset.\n\n-- SECTION 6: CLUSTER CONFIGURATION DEVIATIONS --\n\n[HIGH]     OPS-001  cluster.initial_master_nodes still present in running config\n  Source: elasticsearch.yml (ConfigMap es-config)\n  cluster.initial_master_nodes is a one-time bootstrap setting used only during\n  initial cluster formation. Leaving it in the config of an already-formed cluster\n  is explicitly deprecated in ES 8.x and will cause startup failures in ES 9.x.\n  Remediation: Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes from es-config once the cluster\n  has formed (it is safe to remove from a running cluster at any time).\n\n[HIGH]     OPS-002  All nodes carry combined master+data+ingest roles\n  Source: node settings API + elasticsearch.yml\n  Roles observed: [master, data, ingest] on all three nodes.\n  There are no dedicated master-only nodes. During a rolling restart a node departure\n  triggers both a master re-election and a shard-replica promotion simultaneously,\n  increasing risk of a YELLOW or unavailable window. Minimum recommended for\n  production: 3 dedicated masters + separate data nodes (or at minimum avoid running\n  heavy ingest workloads on master-eligible nodes).\n\n[MEDIUM]   OPS-003  JVM heap set to 512 MiB (below production minimum)\n  Source: StatefulSet env ES_JAVA_OPTS=-Xms512m -Xmx512m\n  512 MiB is below the Elasticsearch-recommended minimum of 1 GiB for production.\n  Under sustained indexing or query load this can cause frequent GC pauses, OOM\n  kills, or shard recovery failures. The memory limit on the container is 2Gi;\n  heap should be set to no more than half of container memory — i.e., -Xms1g -Xmx1g.\n\n[MEDIUM]   OPS-004  No snapshot repository configured\n  Source: GET /_snapshot (implicit — no registered repositories)\n  No backup repository is registered. There is no point-in-time recovery path\n  for data loss, index corruption, or a failed upgrade. A snapshot repository\n  must be configured and tested before any maintenance or upgrade operation.\n\n[MEDIUM]   OPS-005  ILM policy references warm/cold tiers; no warm/cold nodes exist\n  Source: GET /_ilm/policy; GET /_nodes\n  The user-defined ILM policy '180-days-default' transitions to warm at 2d and\n  cold at 30d. All three nodes carry node.attr.tier=hot. Any index managed by\n  this policy will stall at the warm transition (shards unassignable) until\n  warm-tier nodes are added or the policy is updated to skip the warm/cold phases.\n\n[MEDIUM]   OPS-006  StatefulSet update strategy is OnDelete\n  Source: StatefulSet spec\n  Pods are NOT automatically restarted on spec changes. Any image update or\n  config change requires manual pod deletion in reverse ordinal order. Without a\n  documented runbook and maintenance window, this is an operational risk during\n  incidents or upgrades.\n\n[MEDIUM]   OPS-007  audit-index shard routing pinned to require.tier=hot\n  Source: GET /_all/_settings\n  Index setting: routing.allocation.require.tier=hot, _tier_preference=data_content.\n  If any node loses the node.attr.tier=hot label (e.g., during a topology change\n  or node reclassification), all 3 primary shards become unassigned and the\n  cluster degrades to RED for that index.\n\n[INFO]     OPS-008  Version 8.11.1 is not the latest 8.x patch\n  Source: GET /\n  Latest stable 8.x release is 8.17.x. The current version (released 2023-11-11)\n  may have known CVEs or stability fixes addressed in subsequent patch releases.\n  Consult the Elastic release notes and security advisories before scheduling\n  the next maintenance window.\n\n[INFO]     OPS-009  xpack.watcher.encrypt_sensitive_data = false\n  Source: cluster defaults API\n  Watcher credentials (webhook URLs, SMTP passwords, etc.) stored in the .watches\n  index are not encrypted at rest. If Watcher is or will be used, enable\n  xpack.watcher.encrypt_sensitive_data=true and configure a secure settings keystore.\n\n-- SECTION 7: INDEX SECURITY POSTURE --\n\n[INFO]     IDX-001  One user-created index found: audit-index\n  Shards: 3 primary, 1 replica (6 total). Health: GREEN. Documents: 0.\n  No ILM policy is currently attached to this index (no ilm.policy index setting).\n  If this index is intended to hold audit events, attach an appropriate ILM policy\n  and consider enabling index-level security once xpack.security is enabled.\n\n-- SECTION 8: SUMMARY SCORECARD --\n\nSeverity    Count   Items\n---------   -----   ------\nCRITICAL      5     SEC-001, SEC-004, SEC-005, SEC-007, SEC-009\nHIGH          5     SEC-002 (no creds), SEC-003 (Basic license), SEC-006 (FIPS),\n                    SEC-010, SEC-011 (pod/container securityContext),\n                    OPS-001, OPS-002\nMEDIUM        5     OPS-003 thru OPS-007\nINFO          3     SEC-008, OPS-008, OPS-009, IDX-001\n\nTOP PRIORITY REMEDIATION ORDER:\n  1. Enable xpack.security (requires full cluster restart; take snapshot first)\n  2. Enable TLS on HTTP and transport layers simultaneously with step 1\n  3. Create a Kubernetes NetworkPolicy to restrict port 9200/9300 access\n  4. Add container/pod securityContext hardening to the StatefulSet\n  5. Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes from es-config\n  6. Increase JVM heap to -Xms1g -Xmx1g\n  7. Register a snapshot repository and take an initial backup\n  8. Enable xpack.security.audit.enabled=true (requires security from step 1)\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nAll findings are based on read-only API calls and kubectl get/describe.\n=============================================================\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n=============================================================\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with full findings report"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10745,"cache_read_input_tokens":41463,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10745},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2e39a45e-ba5e-4e98-9e88-4501f9cbe38a","uuid":"d4524061-6eab-46e4-b934-28bc924f7ffa","request_id":"req_011Cc2fbRz1HDiDUfDFvf6EY"}
